isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.59) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.27. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.28, p < .001, 95% CI [12.98, 14.09]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.40, p = 0.749, 95% CI [-0.91, 0.66]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.20, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.46, S.E. = 0.32, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.09, -1.83]; Std. beta = -0.55, 95% CI [-0.69, -0.41])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.83, S.E. = 0.36, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.55, -2.12]; Std. beta = -0.63, 95% CI [-0.79, -0.47])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.97, S.E. = 0.48, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.91, -2.02]; Std. beta = -0.66, 95% CI [-0.87, -0.45])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.32, S.E. = 0.54, p < .001, 95% CI [-4.38, -2.25]; Std. beta = -0.74, 95% CI [-0.98, -0.50])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
